T1  - Overdraft banking: An empirical analysis
AU  - Zilberfarb, Ben Zion
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 13
IS  - 6
SP  - 869
EP  - 881
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/12/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(89)90007-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378426689900071
AB  - This study employs, for the first time, regression analysis to examine the behavior of the utilization rate of overdraft limits over time and at the aggregate level. Applying Sprenkle and Millers's (1980) theoretical model to Israeli data, the empirical results show that the wide fluctuations in utilization rates can be well explained. It is therefore possible for the monetary authorities and banks to predict changes in overdraft utilization rates and take the necessary corrective measures. This, in turn, implies that overdraft banking does not hamper the ability of the central and private banks to control credit and reserves.
