T1  - Speculative and precautionary balances as complements in the portfolio: The case of the U.K. banking sector 1972–1980
AU  - Spencer, P.D.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 13
IS  - 6
SP  - 811
EP  - 830
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/12/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(89)90003-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378426689900034
AB  - This paper develops a theory of bank portfolio optimisation which allows for interaction between the precautionary and speculative aspects of the problem. This interaction is a natural feature of the optimisation problem since banks tend to push up interest rates as they respond to a loss of cash and reserves, inducing capital losses on their fixed-interest assets. The implication is that banks should take their precautionary balances into account when assessing their speculative positions, and vice versa, so that these can act as complements in the portfolio. The empirical results confirm that this was an important aspect of U.K. bank behaviour during the 1970s.
ER  - 

